\ltrpar\ql\rtlch\af1\afs24\ltrch\f2\fs24 {\highlight7 <CH2>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even a sin committed under duress needs to be forgiven, because many times a person 
allows himself to be placed in a predicament in which he is compelled to sin (e.g., leaving the office 
at a very late hour on the eve of Shabbos or Festival).—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This would include not giving charity with a whole heart, and not helping a needy fellow 
Jew.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The literal meaning of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e1\'cc\'c4\'e1\'c0\'ec\'c4\'e9 \'e3\'c7\'f2\'c7\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is “without knowledge,” and it implies not using our 
intellectual capabilities to study the laws of Torah and therewith gain the “knowledge” needed to 
observe the commandments properly.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes the sins of making vows and oaths (even though they are kept), verbally 
insulting one’s fellowmen, and directing one’s displeasure against the decrees of Hashem.— 
Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}A sin committed publicly could very well cause {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c4\'ec\'e5\'cc\'ec \'e4'{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , the desecration of Hashem’s Name, 
and may also lead others to sin. A sin committed in secret, indicates that the sinner fears the 
reaction of people but is unafraid of Hashem’s displeasure.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This also includes such things that arouse desire for forbidden sexual relationships, such as 
embracing or dancing.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes speaking the words of Torah in unclean places, cursing, humiliating someone; 
speaking of business matters on Shabbos, revealing another person’s secret, telling jokes and 
holding idle conversations in a house of worship (and certainly during the actual prayers) and 
telling lies.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes false advertising and dishonesty in business matters.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Evil thoughts, lustful thoughts, heretical thoughts, and suspicious thoughts about righteous 
people are included.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to confession of sins without feeling regret for committing them and without 
earnest resolve to correct them in the future.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Any gathering or intimate meeting for the purpose of sexual immortality is 
included.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Not obeying their commands, not rising for a talmudic scholar and disrespect for one’s 
teacher even if he is not considered a “Torah Great” are included.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes using physical, political or financial power to harm someone.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This involves any sin committed that becomes public knowledge, including improper 
conduct with one’s fellow man.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to idle talk and gossip.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes profanity and unclean language.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When a person allows his Evil Inclination to rule over him, he commits a sin.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We ask Hashem to pardon us even for sins we are not aware that we committed, and also 
for such sins through which we caused damage but are not aware of the amount of loss 
incurred.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}A bribe is not limited to money or gifts; it includes flattery or personal favors.— Siddur 
HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes causing a fellow Jew physical, monetary of social harm through passing 
degrading information about him to another person. It makes no difference whether this is done 
in his presence or behind his back, or if the information is true or false.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Ridicule of a person, a commandment, or guards of Torah are all included in the sin of 
scoffing.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This would include overcharging, misrepresenting, falselabeling and all other such 
deceitful practices.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Eating forbidden (nonkosher) foods, not saying the proper blessing or grace after meals, 
overeating, are included in this sin.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to using the eyes to gaze at forbidden things.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes idle gossip, which is certainly forbidden in the synagogue at all times.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Speaking “with chutzpah” to Torah scholars, or to someone more learned than himself is 
included in {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'c7\'e6\'cc\'e5\'cc\'fa \'ee\'c5\'f6\'c7\'e7{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch .\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*27>}27{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rejecting an obligation to fulfill even a single commandment. Also included is shirking a 
religious obligation which must then be assumed by someone else.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*28>}28{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes a “Dayan,” a judge who does not render correct decisions, and it also includes 
not giving someone the benefit of the doubt.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*29>}29{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes even attempting to harm someone; even if no harm was actually done, he still 
needs forgiveness.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*30>}30{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Not doing a favor, not giving charity properly, and feeling bad at someone else’s success 
are included.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*31>}31{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Lightmindedness or frivolity in the synagogue or Bais Midrash or while wearing tefillin are 
serious sins.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*32>}32{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rejecting admonition and “ignoring” punishment are included. Also included is brushing 
aside illness, financial loss, and humiliation as mere coincidences rather than manifestations of 
Divine displeasure.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*33>}33{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to carrying tales, even true ones, about one person to another, and the one who 
listens to these tales is also included in this category of sin.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*34>}34{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes swearing falsely or even swearing a useless oath.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*35>}35{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hating someone because of jealousy, or because he doesn’t conform to your ideas of 
ettiquete.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*36>}36{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Denying that you owe someone a monetary debt when he asks for payment.—Siddur 
HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*37>}37{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This includes sins committed because of confusion, worry or pain, it also includes the sin of 
harboring doubts about the authenticity of the laws enacted by our Sages, and doubts about the 
fundamental principles of our faith, such as Divine Providence, reward and punishment, and also 
doubts about the authenticity of the Torah and the Prophets.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*38>}38{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}A burntoffering is brought for failure to fulfill any positive commandment, e.g, putting on 
nonkosher tefillin.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*39>}39{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}A sinoffering is brought for unintentionally transgressing any prohibitive commandment 
punishable  by excision ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c5\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) if it were done with intent.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*40>}40{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The fluctuating offering is an offering that varies in value according to the financial means 
of the individual who brings it. (The literal meaning of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'e5\'c9\'ec\'c8\'e4 \'e5\'c0\'e9\'e5\'c9\'f8\'c5\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , is “go up and down”). This type 
of offering is brought when a person swore falsely (unintentionally) concerning something he did 
or did not do. For example, one may have thought he ate something and consequently swore that 
he ate it, but in reality he did not and thus he swore falsely.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*41>}41{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This type of sacrifice was brought in an instance where it is uncertain whether or not a 
violation occurred. For example it is not known whether a substance he ate was of a forbidden 
nature or if it was permitted.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*42>}42{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}A Rabbinic Court had the right to impose lashing for a violation of a rabbinic injunction.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*43>}43{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Forty lashes proscribed by the Torah was given to one who actively and intentionally 
violated any of the prohibitive commandments, providing he was forewarned and the act was 
witnessed by two witnesses.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*44>}44{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}One who intentionally does work or eats on Yom Kippur, or one who eats chometz — 
leavened bread — on Pesach, is punished with excision and childlessness.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*45>}45{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Stoning is the penalty for knowingly desecrating Shabbos, burning is the penalty for certain 
forbidden sexual relationships, beheading is the penalty for murder, and strangulation is the 
penalty for adultery.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*46>}46{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}For example returning the stolen money would be a corrective measure for the prohibition 
of stealing.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*47>}47{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Devorim 29:28.\par
{\highlight7 <CH6>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Light is sown for the righteous in this world, but the harvest of that light awaits the future 
world.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @sn}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}Others say that while the light may sometimes be hidden like the seed in the earth, it is sure to 
spring forth.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Tehillim 97:11.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The court of man.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Anyone who has transgressed either a law of the Torah or Rabbinic law is called an 
“Avaryan” (transgressor) and is subject to excommunication from the community and hence 
cannot be included in any prayer or service which requires a quorum. (See Periesha to Tur 
Shulchan Aruch section 619, also Shulchan Aruch Yoreh Deah 324). Special permission is thus 
required in order to include them in our prayers. The above declaration is based on a talmudic 
statement: “Rabbi Shimon Chasidah says: A public fast wherein Jewish transgressors do not 
participate is not a [true] fast.” This is deduced from the fact that though the odor of galbanum is 
unpleasant, Scripture included it among the fragrant spices of the incenseoffering.—Maseches 
Kerisos 6b\par
{\highlight7 @sn}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Bach (Ibid.) permission granted is not a blanket dispensation but is predicated on 
the assumption that these transgressors will repent. This is implied in the words: {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'c7\'ec \'e3\'c7\'f2\'c7\'fa \'e4\'c7\'ee\'c8\'f7\'e5\'c9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , with 
the consent of Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The prototypical vow is as follows: “This item shall be forbidden to me just as a sacrifice” 
(See Ritva, Ran Nedarim 2a).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}An oath is a declaration made by someone to do, or not to do something. The difference 
between a vow and an oath is that a vow makes an object forbidden whereas an oath makes some 
action forbidden (or obligatory) on the part of the person who makes the oath.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}During the times Holy Temple, people could dedicate anything to the Temple. It henceforth 
became forbidden to anyone, and allowed to be used only for the Temple.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The prototypical expression above (in note 5) ends with “as a sacrifice” which in Hebrew is 
“as a korban.” In place of the word “korban” the word “konam” was frequently used. There is a 
dispute in Maseches Nedarim as to the origin of the word.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This means that the entire prototypical expression as given in note 5 is not used.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See note 7 above. In this case the word “korban” is replaced with “kanos.”\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to things dedicated to the Holy Temple.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Only vows or oaths made by an individual concerning himself can be nullified, but not 
those made by others even though they effect him. He also cannot nullify oaths that he took at the 
behest of a Beth Din or by a second party.—Tur 619\par
{\highlight7 <CH7>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shabbos, more than other days, lends itself to offering praise and thanksgiving to Hashem. 
When man rests from his physical labor and is relieved of material concerns, his soul is free to 
pursue the intellectual and spiritual aspects of life. These pursuits lead him to serve Hashem and 
to praise Him.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We will proclaim His kindliness in the morning of redemption. And while yet in the 
darkness of exile, we proclaim our belief in His faithfulness.—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Shabbos day of rest affords me the opportunity to observe and appreciate the greatness 
of Your work.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s ‘works’ are the visible creation, while His ‘thoughts’ are the Divine purpose 
behind each created thing.—Seporno\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Others translate, ‘You have increased my might like that of the wild ram.’\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The palm and the cedar both enjoy a long life span and flourish during all seasons. Thus they 
symbolize the lasting happiness of the righteous in contrast to the short prosperity of the wicked.\par
{\highlight7 <CH8>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}These are the gates of sunrise and sunset through which Hashem, in His infinite wisdom, has 
divided life on earth into two complementary halves.—Rabbi S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He alternates the three daily periods—evening, morning, and afternoon.—Avudraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The stars appear as watchmen appointed by Hashem to stand guard over the sleeping world 
below. He also appointed them their places in definite orbits according to His will and for 
purposes known to Him alone.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}His Name {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e4' \'f6\'c0\'e1\'c8\'e0\'e5\'c9\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  means “He Who takes all the infinite variety of hosts and creatures and 
unites them to act and interact as parts of one unified Universe.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This prayer is an abbreviated form of the {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c7\'e4\'c2\'e1\'c8\'e4 \'f8\'c7\'e1\'cc\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  prayer in the morning service. It thanks 
Hashem for the sacred gift of Divine Revelation that He granted Yisrael. It declares that Torah 
alone is the eternal heritage of the Jewish people and that all other goods and gifts of life are 
transitory.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All that we have affirmed in the Shema, is true and trustworthy.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He redeemed us from Pharaoh, and saved us from Sichon and Og in the days of Moshe and 
from the thirtyone kings in the days of Yehoshua.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Tyrants” include Amalek and others who wanted to destroy us.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Malbim says that “oppressors” ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f6\'c8\'f8\'c5\'e9\'f0\'e5\'cc{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) refers to those who actively persecute us whereas 
“enemies” ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'e5\'c9\'e9\'c0\'e1\'c5\'e9\'f0\'e5\'cc{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) refers to those who would rejoice over our misfortune without necessarily 
contributing to our downfall in an outright manner.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Great things” refers to the way Hashem rules according to the laws of nature and 
“wonders” refers to those things that are classified as miracles.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Not only does Hashem sustain our souls in exile but He also sustains our physical 
wellbeing.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The redemption from Egypt is the source for all later redemptions; it is the source from 
which our final and total salvation will spring. We became free, never again to taste the bitterness 
of spiritual or physical bondage.—Sfas Emes\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 15:11\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 15:2\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 15:18\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yirmiyahu 31:10\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Undisturbed peace, and strength for a new day of vigorous living are the gifts that night 
brings and for which we pray to Hashem.— S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We particularly ask of Him at night to bless us with wise counsel. Daytime is the time for 
achievement, but the rest that comes with nightfall is made to allow man to compose his thoughts. 
By virtue of the complete relaxation it affords, sleep endows the mind and spirit with renewed 
vigor. We pray therefore for Divine aid so that our nightly rest will help us take wise counsel and 
affirm worthy resolution for future days.—Avudraham and Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shield us from trouble before it comes, and remove it from us if it has already come.—Siach 
Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Hebrew word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d2\'c8\'e8\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (Satan) used in the Prayer Book refers to the Evil Impulse, the lower 
passions which are a hindrance to man’s pursuit of the nobler aims in life. It is against the 
dominance of this impulse that the Jew prays. The “adversary,” therefore, is any person, spirit, or 
Evil Impulse that seduces us to do wrong.—Dover Sholom and others\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 31:16±17. This is merely metaphorical, since Hashem, of course, does not become 
tired, nor does He require rest.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rabbi Yonasan Eibschitz in his sefer, Yaaros Devash, explains that upon reflecting in Whose 
Presence he is about to pray, man should be so overwhelmed with awe and trepidation that he is 
unable to open his lips. He therefore prefaces his prayer by beseeching Hashem, to open his lips, 
asking His help to be able to pray in His Presence.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Because these are days of judgment and our lives hang in the balance, we pray to Hashem 
to remember us for life (Rashi, Levush).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This is based on Yechezkel 18:32, ‘For I do not desire the death of him that dies, but rather 
that he repent from his evil ways and live.’\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the Book in which the righteous are inscribed for life everlasting.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We ask Hashem to grant us life for His sake, i.e., so that we can fulfill His commandments.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*27>}27{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We proclaim and accept His Kingship on Rosh Hashanah.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*28>}28{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He helps us during the Ten Days of Penitence, by accepting our repentance.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*29>}29{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He delivers us on Yom Kippur by forgiving our sins.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*30>}30{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}On Sukkos, as His Divine Cloud of Glory, hovers over us, He shields us from spiritual and 
physical danger (Shaare Shomayim).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*31>}31{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s rule of the world is permanent and perpetual (Kuzari).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*32>}32{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Here we emphatically declare our belief in the immortality of the soul (Kuzari).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*33>}33{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Deliverance is not a sudden happening but rather a process of growth or sprouting.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*34>}34{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even if we are not worthy of life by virtue of our deeds, inscribe us for life because You are 
a merciful Father (Siddur Chasidei Ashkenaz).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*35>}35{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , ‘and so,’ marks the beginning of the special prayers of the Shemoneh Esreh 
recited at each Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur service. According to Avudraham, the Sages chose 
this word to convey the thought expressed by Esther as she prepared to go before the king on 
behalf of her people. After telling Mordechai to assemble all the Jews to fast for three days and 
nights on her behalf, she said, “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  and so I will go in to the king” (Esther 4:16). Thus, 
since today is the Day of Judgment, as we come before the Supreme King of kings, the Holy One 
Blessed is He, we begin with the words uttered by Esther as she came before the king. The Siddur 
Maggid Tzedek quoted by Siach Yitzchak writes that the emphasis of Avudraham was on the last 
words of the verse said by Esther, “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e0\'c2\'f9\'d1\'c6\'f8 \'ec\'c9\'e0 \'eb\'c7\'e3\'cc\'c8\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ,” “And so I will go into the king, 
even if it is unlawful,” for which one of us can say, “I am virtuous, I have cleansed my heart from 
sin.” Especially on this great and awesome Day of Judgment, who among us is not embarrassed 
and ashamed to appear before the King of kings garbed in sackcloths of sin. If Esther who had 
fasted for three days in penitence and prayer in preparation for her appearance before the king 
was nevertheless so terribly frightened that she declared: “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e0\'c2\'f9\'d1\'c6\'f8 \'ec\'c9\'e0 \'eb\'c7\'e3\'cc\'c8\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ” then we 
should certainly tremble in awe before the presence of Hashem on this Day of Judgment, knowing 
deep in our hearts how little and how poorly we have prepared ourselves. Thus our Sages 
ordained that we open the prayers with the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  recalling the words of Esther; therewith 
shattering our delusions of spiritual complacency, and causing us to bow before Him with broken 
hearts and tearfilled eyes.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*36>}36{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'fa\'cc\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  implies {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'fa\'cc\'c8\'f0\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a gift. We ask Hashem to grant us the feeling of reverence for Him, 
as a gift, knowing how difficult it is to attain such a high level of reverence completely on our own 
(Siach Yitzchok).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*37>}37{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'f2\'c2\'f9\'d2\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , lit., Your works, indicates that which has attained or is near perfection. 
Thus Yisrael is called His works since we have accepted His Kingship and His Torah which is the 
fulfillment of Hashem’s creation (Siach Yitzchok).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*38>}38{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All you have created, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c6\'e1\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c8\'e0\'fa\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , indicates that which has not attained its fulfillment, thus we 
ask Hashem to cast His dread even on those people who have not yet accepted His Divine 
Kingdom (Siach Yitzchok).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*39>}39{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nation of Yisrael will fear You.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*40>}40{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nations of the world will finally prostrate themselves before You, i.e. submit to You and 
accept the yoke of Your Kingship.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*41>}41{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Once all of Your works and created beings have submitted themselves to Your rule and 
formed a single bond to do Your will, the honor of Yisrael will be established and raised to new 
heights. It will then be apparent to all that Yisrael alone carried the yoke of Hashem’s Kingdom 
throughout the bitter years of exile, giving Him obedience despite its suffering and persecution 
and the taunts of those who cynically asked, “Where is Your God?” (Etz Yosef).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*42>}42{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who fear Hashem will then be praiseworthy in the eyes of all men.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*43>}43{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Men will no longer consider as ridiculous those who seek Hashem and search for ways to 
serve Him.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*44>}44{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who wait upon Him will no longer be subdued but will voice their convictions freely.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*45>}45{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Tehillim 132:17. The climax of this spiritual renaissance will be the restoration of our 
people to our land under the scepter of the Moshiach, descendant of Dovid, the anointed of 
Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*46>}46{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The entire universe was created for the sake of Yisrael in order that Hashem’s Divine 
Influence be attached to it. This essence (Yisrael) was created for the sake of an even more 
treasured essence, namely the prophets and the pious among them. This gradation forms the basis 
of the sequence of the Rosh Hashanah±Yom Kippur prayers: “Grant that Your awe be upon all that 
You have made,” is the first prayer. It is followed by, “Grant honor to Your people,” and finally by 
“the righteous will see this and rejoice.” Thus the righteous and pious are the purpose and 
fulfillment of the entire creation, the true reason for celebrating these holy days (Fundamentals of 
Kuzari, page 59).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*47>}47{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Forgiveness, ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c0\'e7\'c4\'e9\'ec\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) implies a waiver of punishment which is due the guilty party.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*48>}48{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Pardon, ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f1\'c0\'ec\'c4\'e9\'e7\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) implies that the earlier relationship between the sinner and the Pardoner 
will not be blemished because of the wrongdoing of the sinner.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*49>}49{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Atonement ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c7\'f4\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) implies total acquittal of the consequences of our wrongful acts.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*50>}50{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Were it not for the intervention of the wondrous power of Hashem’s grace, our moral and 
physical entity would have long ceased, as a consequence of our transgressions. This would have 
been our fate in accordance with the law of cause and effect which functions in Hashem’s world 
according to His will. It is only Hashem Himself, He Who originally ordained that law, Who in the 
omnipotence of His will, can also suspend that law. Only He can cause the wrong which was done 
to become as if it had never occurred. Only Hashem can uproot in its entirety the sin and 
consequential effect of sin. He has assured this wondrous power of His benevolent grace to every 
Jew who fulfills the true purpose of Yom Kippur by doing teshuva, true repentance. Thus we cry 
out to Him “Blot out and remove our transgressions and sins from before Your eyes” for in the 
words of the prophet, Hashem alone blots out our transgressions.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*51>}51{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Were Hashem to destroy us because of our transgressions, His Name would be desecrated 
among the nations of the world. Thus says the prophet, He blots out our transgressions for His own 
sake.—Metsudas Dovid\par
{\highlight7 @sn}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Malbim, “for My own sake” implies for the sake of the favor and lovingkindness 
which is His attribute ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c4\'e9 \'e7\'c8\'f4\'c5\'f5 \'e7\'c6\'f1\'c6\'e3 \'e0\'c8\'f0\'c4\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*52>}52{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yeshaya 42:25. This implies that our sins will be blotted out so thoroughly that not even the 
slightest trace will remain. Thus says Hashem, “and your sins, I will not recall” because there will 
be nothing left to recall.—Metsudas Dovid\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*53>}53{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f4\'cc\'c0\'f9\'d1\'c8\'f2\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , your transgressions, which implies a wanton disregard of Hashem’s will is 
compared to an {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'c8\'e1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a thick cloud. Just as a thick cloud darkens the earth so too, our transgressions 
cause darkness in our lives.—Malbim\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*54>}54{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c7\'e8\'cc\'c9\'e0\'fa\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , your sins, which implies error, or sins committed unknowingly, is 
compared to an {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'c8\'f0\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a mist cloud, which does not cause such terrible darkness. So too, our sins do 
not create such severe blackness in our lives.—Malbim\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*55>}55{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yeshaya 44:22\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*56>}56{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}In our translation, the words, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c4\'eb\'cc\'c9\'ec \'e7\'c7\'e8\'c9\'e0\'fa\'c5\'e9\'eb\'c6\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  are joined with the words {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ec\'c4\'f4\'c0\'f0\'c5\'e9 \'e4' \'fa\'cc\'c4\'e8\'c0\'e4\'c8\'f8\'e5\'cc{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , thus reading 
“from all your sins before Adonoy, you will be cleansed”; implying that the entire sentence is a 
statement of fact, i.e., that Yom Kippur is a day in which Hashem atones our sins. According to 
Targum Yonassan ben Uziel, however, the words {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c4\'eb\'cc\'c9\'ec \'e7\'c7\'e8\'c9\'e0\'fa\'c5\'e9\'eb\'c6\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  are joined to the previous 
words—{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ec\'c0\'e8\'c7\'e4\'c5\'f8 \'e0\'c6\'fa\'c0\'eb\'c6\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch —changing the entire concept of the sentence. According to the Targum the 
sentence reads: {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c4\'e9 \'e1\'c7\'e9\'cc\'e5\'c9\'ed \'e4\'c7\'e6\'c6\'e4 \'e9\'c0\'eb\'c7\'f4\'cc\'c5\'f8 \'f2\'c2\'ec\'c5\'e9\'eb\'c6\'ed \'ec\'c0\'e8\'c7\'e4\'c5\'f8 \'e0\'c6\'fa\'c0\'eb\'c6\'ed \'ee\'c4\'eb\'cc\'c9\'ec \'e7\'c7\'e8\'c9\'e0\'fa\'c5\'e9\'eb\'c6\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch . “For on this day He will make atonement 
