{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*130>}130{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}May His sovereignty be revealed.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*131>}131{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We pray that the redemption will come speedily and that the process of the redemption 
itself will not be prolonged.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*132>}132{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This phrase, the heart of the Kaddish, is found almost verbatim in Daniel 2:20.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*133>}133{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The ten expressions of praise in the Kaddish refer to the ten utterances by which Hashem 
created the world. (See Maseches Avos 5:1.)\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*134>}134{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}May Hashem be praised and exalted far beyond all the blessings, hymns and praises that 
are uttered.—Mishnah Berurah in the name of the Vilna Gaon 56:14.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*135>}135{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Consolations are uttered because Hashem is in mourning over the destruction of the Holy 
Temple and the exile of His people.\par
{\highlight7 <CH11>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Since it was Solomon who built the Temple, why is its inauguration attributed to Dovid? 
Rashi explains: Dovid composed the song which would be sung at the inauguration later, in 
Solomon’s days.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Radak writes that the Hebrew word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e3\'c4\'ec\'c4\'e9\'fa\'c8\'f0\'c4\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is an expression used to describe either a 
downtrodden or an uplifted state. The downtrodden state of the Jewish people is actually part of 
their uplifting says the Sfas Emes, as it is said, “when I was brought low, He delivered me” 
(Tehillim 116:6). “My downtrodden state was the cause of my salvation,” proclaims Dovid, just as 
when one lowers a bucket ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e3\'c0\'ec\'c4\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) into a well in order to bring up the water.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The literal translation of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e6\'c5\'eb\'c6\'f8 \'f7\'c8\'e3\'c0\'f9\'d1\'e5{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is His ‘holy remembrance,’ but it refers to His Name; for the 
titles we bestow upon Him are our means of remembering Him.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}A moment is a measure of time. Hashem’s anger is limited to time (be it long or short) but 
Hashem’s favor is unlimited.—Sfas Emes\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The literal translation of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'c8\'e1\'e5\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is glory. Rabbi Yerucham Levovitz explained that the soul is 
called {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'c8\'e1\'e5\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  because its only function is to give glory to Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s saying and doing are synonymous and simultaneous as it is said, “By the word of 
Hashem the heavens were made” (Tehillim 33:6).—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Says and does” refers to those things that are not lasting and must be renewed whereas, “He 
decrees and fulfills,” refers to those things that have {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f7\'c4\'e9\'e5\'cc\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , and last forever.—Tzelosa d’Avraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Not only is Hashem’s compassionate providence concerned with the earth and enduring 
things, but His compassion and providence extend even to those creatures which are destined to 
perish.—Avudraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem redeems those who are in captivity and saves others from being taken in captivity.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Make His Divine attributes (mercy, kindness, etc.) known to the world.—Siach Yitzchok\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Jew should be proud at being found worthy to utter Hashem’s Name.—Siddur HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Seeking Hashem is an end in itself and provides joy to those who earnestly seek 
Him.—Siach Yitzchok\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}His “miracles” were witnessed by Jew and Egyptian alike in Egypt. His “laws” are the 
Torah He gave us at Mt. Sinai.—Iyun Tefillah\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The entire section—the previous verses as well as the following verses—are addressed to 
the Jewish People, who are the seed of Yisrael, the chosen of Hashem, who are asked to remember 
His wonders, miracles and laws.—Tzelosa d’Avraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This verse in following the preceding verse indicates that the original covenant which 
Hashem made with Avraham was later confirmed to Yitzchok in an oath and then established for 
Yaakov as a statute. After Yaakov was given the name Yisrael, it became an everlasting 
covenant.—Tzelosa d’Avraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Both Pharaoh and Avimelech were admonished for Avraham’s sake (Bereishis 13:17; 
20:3,7).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Hebrew word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch  \'ee\'c0\'f9\'d1\'c4\'e9\'e7\'c8\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  can also be translated as “My great ones” and as such refers to the 
Patriarchs. “My prophets” refers to the Matriarchs, who were known to be prophets. Both were 
afforded extraordinary Divine protection.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Siach Yitzchok maintains that this verse directs Jewry to sing to Hashem in all the lands in 
which they are dispersed during their exile. Tzelosa d’Avraham understands the verse to direct all 
the nations of the earth to sing to Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}a) We are to proclaim our deliverance by Hashem every day; b) We are to proclaim that our 
