HaGra\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Etz Yosef understands this as the “holy splendor” of Hashem’s Sanctuary. Tzelosa 
d’Avraham sees it as the splendor and joy of worship before Hashem, as contrasted with secular, 
frivolous manifestations of beauty and splendor.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Simcha (rejoicing) describes one’s feelings at a new experience of happiness, whereas gila 
(exultation) describes the feeling one experiences over an ongoing situation of joy. Since there is 
nothing new on the earth {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch  \'e5\'c0\'e0\'c5\'e9\'ef \'eb\'cc\'c8\'ec\'e7\'c8\'e3\'c8\'f9\'d1 \'fa\'cc\'c7\'e7\'c7\'fa \'e4\'c7\'f9\'cc\'d1\'c8\'ee\'c6\'f9\'d1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (Koheles 1:9), it is said the earth will exult (gila); but 
the heavens will rejoice (simcha) because there is {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c4\'e9\'e3\'e5\'cc\'f9\'d1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  in the heavens.—Gaon of Vilna\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The fact that we are privileged to sing Your praises and cling to You will make us 
praiseworthy.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Holy Temple.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Or Holy is it—i.e., the Temple.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Mount Moriah upon which the Holy Temple was built is holy itself even when the Temple 
is destroyed. The previous verse refers to the time of the Temple, the second verse refers to the 
period of its destruction.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*27>}27{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c6\'f1\'c6\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (kindness) is the good Hashem bestows without a promise, whereas {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c1\'ee\'c6\'fa {\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (truth) is the 
fulfillment of His promise.—Siach Yitzchok\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*28>}28{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s mercies to mankind started from the very day that Adam was created. Hashem 
created the world in order to fill it with kindness as it is said: “A world of kindness was built” 
(Tehillim 89:3).—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*29>}29{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Attribute your victories to Hashem’s might rather than to your own.—Siach Yitzchok. 
Rashbam and others hold that since Hashem’s actions are a reflection of Yisrael’s deeds, the latter 
are, in a sense, the source of His might. Thus when Yisrael follows the wishes of Hashem, they give 
might to Him.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*30>}30{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}There is a spiritual Temple in the heavens which corresponds to the Temple on 
earth.—Radak. The Talmud (Maseches Zevachim 115b) notes that the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch  \'ee\'c4\'ee\'cc\'c4\'f7\'c0\'e3\'cc\'c8\'f9\'d1\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  may also be 
read {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c4\'ee\'c0\'f7\'e5\'cc\'e3\'c8\'f9\'d1\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , from Your holy people, indicating that Hashem is especially demanding of the most 
adherent to the Torah. When this occurs, the world is filled with awe and fear of Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*31>}31{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}These two verses (94:1±2) are an appeal to Hashem during a time fraught with the 
sufferings of exile, when it seems as if Hashem has forsaken His people. He is urged to reveal 
Himself as the Mighty champion of justice—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*32>}32{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Only Hashem knows what is true deliverance for a person. Prayer is not always answered, 
because Hashem in His infinite wisdom knows that granting the request is not always for our 
benefit. We must therefore bless and offer thanks to Hashem regardless of whether our petition 
has been granted.—Siach Yitzchok\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*33>}33{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Radak understands Dovid to be asking Hashem to raise the People of Yisrael above their 
enemies. Ibn Ezra says that Hashem is being asked to act like a shepherd who brings his flock to 
high ground to save them from beasts of prey.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*34>}34{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We hope to earn redemption through our deeds, but if we are found wanting, then “show 
us Your kindness”—overlook our deficiencies and “grant” us salvation.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*35>}35{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Request all that you desire and I will fulfill every request.—Ibn Ezra. The Yerushalayim 
Talmud (Maseches Taanis 3:6) indicates that the more one requests Hashem’s providence—the 
“wider he opens his mouth”—the more he shows his belief in Hashem’s ability to provide all of 
man’s needs.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*36>}36{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The foremost level of man’s trust in Hashem is manifested in three situations: a){\highlight7 <TIE>}when he is 
