{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s rule of the world is permanent and perpetual (Kuzari).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Here we emphatically declare our belief in the immortality of the soul (Kuzari).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Deliverance is not a sudden happening but rather a process of growth or sprouting.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even if we are not worthy of life by virtue of our deeds, inscribe us for life because You are 
a merciful Father (Siddur Chasidei Ashkenaz).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , ‘and so,’ marks the beginning of the special prayers of the Shemoneh Esreh 
recited at each Rosh Hashanah and Yom Kippur service. According to Avudraham, the Sages 
chose this word to convey the thought expressed by Esther as she prepared to go before the king 
on behalf of her people. After telling Mordechai to assemble all the Jews to fast for three days and 
nights on her behalf, she said, “ {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  and so I will go in to the king” (Esther 4:16). Thus, 
since today is the Day of Judgment, as we come before the Supreme King of kings, the Holy One 
Blessed is He, we begin with the words uttered by Esther as she came before the king. The Siddur 
Maggid Tzedek quoted by Siach Yitzchak writes that the emphasis of Avudraham was on the last 
words of the verse said by Esther, “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e0\'c2\'f9\'d1\'c6\'f8 \'ec\'c9\'e0 \'eb\'c7\'e3\'cc\'c8\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ,” “And so I will go into the king, 
even if it is unlawful,” for which one of us can say, “I am virtuous, I have cleansed my heart from 
sin.” Especially on this great and awesome Day of Judgment, who among us is not embarrassed 
and ashamed to appear before the King of kings garbed in sackcloths of sin. If Esther who had 
fasted for three days in penitence and prayer in preparation for her appearance before the king 
was nevertheless so terribly frightened that she declared: “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e0\'c2\'f9\'d1\'c6\'f8 \'ec\'c9\'e0 \'eb\'c7\'e3\'cc\'c8\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ” then we 
should certainly tremble in awe before the presence of Hashem on this Day of Judgment, knowing 
deep in our hearts how little and how poorly we have prepared ourselves. Thus our Sages 
ordained that we open the prayers with the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  recalling the words of Esther; therewith 
shattering our delusions of spiritual complacency, and causing us to bow before Him with broken 
hearts and tearfilled eyes.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'fa\'cc\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  implies {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'fa\'cc\'c8\'f0\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a gift. We ask Hashem to grant us the feeling of reverence for Him, 
as a gift, knowing how difficult it is to attain such a high level of reverence completely on our own 
(Siach Yitzchok).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'f2\'c2\'f9\'d2\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , lit., Your works, indicates that which has attained or is near perfection. 
Thus Yisrael is called His works since we have accepted His Kingship and His Torah which is the 
fulfillment of Hashem’s creation (Siach Yitzchok).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All you have created, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c6\'e1\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c8\'e0\'fa\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , indicates that which has not attained its fulfillment, thus we 
ask Hashem to cast His dread even on those people who have not yet accepted His Divine 
Kingdom (Siach Yitzchok).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nation of Yisrael will fear You.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nations of the world will finally prostrate themselves before You, i.e. submit to You and 
accept the yoke of Your Kingship.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Once all of Your works and created beings have submitted themselves to Your rule and 
formed a single bond to do Your will, the honor of Yisrael will be established and raised to new 
heights. It will then be apparent to all that Yisrael alone carried the yoke of Hashem’s Kingdom 
throughout the bitter years of exile, giving Him obedience despite its suffering and persecution 
and the taunts of those who cynically asked, “Where is Your God?” (Etz Yosef).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who fear Hashem will then be praiseworthy in the eyes of all men.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who seek Hashem and search for ways to serve Him will no longer be considered 
ridiculous.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who wait upon Him will no longer be subdued but will voice their convictions freely.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Tehillim 132:17. The climax of this spiritual renaissance will be the restoration of our 
people to our land under the scepter of the Moshiach, descendant of Dovid, the anointed of 
Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The entire universe was created for the sake of Yisrael in order that Hashem’s Divine 
Influence be attached to it. This essence (Yisrael) was created for the sake of an even more 
treasured essence, namely the prophets and the pious among them. This gradation forms the basis 
of the sequence of the Rosh Hashanah±Yom Kippur prayers: “Grant that Your awe be upon all that 
You have made,” is the first prayer. It is followed by, “Grant honor to Your people,” and finally by 
“the righteous will see this and rejoice.” Thus the righteous and pious are the purpose and 
fulfillment of the entire creation, the true reason for celebrating these holy days (Fundamentals of 
Kuzari, page 59).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Forgiveness, ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c0\'e7\'c4\'e9\'ec\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) implies a waiver of punishment which is due the guilty party.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*27>}27{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Pardon, ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f1\'c0\'ec\'c4\'e9\'e7\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) implies that the earlier relationship between the sinner and the Pardoner 
will not be blemished because of the wrongdoing of the sinner.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*28>}28{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Atonement ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c7\'f4\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) implies total acquittal of the consequences of our wrongful acts.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*29>}29{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Were it not for the intervention of the wondrous power of Hashem’s grace, our moral and 
physical entity would have long ceased, as a consequence of our transgressions. This would have 
been our fate in accordance with the law of cause and effect which functions in Hashem’s world 
according to His will. It is only Hashem Himself, He Who originally ordained that law, Who in the 
omnipotence of His will, can also suspend that law. Only He can cause the wrong which was done 
to become as if it had never occurred. Only Hashem can uproot in its entirety the sin and 
consequential effect of sin. He has assured this wondrous power of His benevolent grace to every 
Jew who fulfills the true purpose of Yom Kippur by doing teshuva, true repentance. Thus we cry 
out to Him “Blot out and remove our transgressions and sins from before Your eyes” for in the 
words of the prophet, Hashem alone blots out our transgressions.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*30>}30{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Were Hashem to destroy us because of our transgressions, His Name would be desecrated 
among the nations of the world. Thus says the prophet, He blots out our transgressions for His 
own sake.—Metsudas Dovid\par
{\highlight7 @sn}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Malbim, “for My own sake” implies for the sake of the favor and lovingkindness 
which is His attribute ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c4\'e9 \'e7\'c8\'f4\'c5\'f5 \'e7\'c6\'f1\'c6\'e3 \'e0\'c8\'f0\'c4\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*31>}31{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yeshaya 42:25. This implies that our sins will be blotted out so thoroughly that not even the 
slightest trace will remain. Thus says Hashem, “and your sins, I will not recall” because there will 
be nothing left to recall.—Metsudas Dovid\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*32>}32{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f4\'cc\'c0\'f9\'d1\'c8\'f2\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , your transgressions, which implies a wanton disregard of Hashem’s will is 
compared to an {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'c8\'e1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a thick cloud. Just as a thick cloud darkens the earth so too, our transgressions 
cause darkness in our lives.—Malbim\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*33>}33{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c7\'e8\'cc\'c9\'e0\'fa\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , your sins, which implies error, or sins committed unknowingly, is 
compared to an {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f2\'c8\'f0\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a mist cloud, which does not cause such terrible darkness. So too, our sins do 
not create such severe blackness in our lives.—Malbim\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*34>}34{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yeshaya 44:22\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*35>}35{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}In our translation, the words, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c4\'eb\'cc\'c9\'ec \'e7\'c7\'e8\'c9\'e0\'fa\'c5\'e9\'eb\'c6\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  are joined with the words {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ec\'c4\'f4\'c0\'f0\'c5\'e9 \'e4' \'fa\'cc\'c4\'e8\'c0\'e4\'c8\'f8\'e5\'cc{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , thus reading 
“from all your sins before Adonoy, you will be cleansed”; implying that the entire sentence is a 
