cleansed.” Klei Yakar, obviously influenced by Targum explicitly states that this sentence is not a 
blanket promise of atonement, for Yom Kippur atones only for those who cleanse themselves with 
honest repentance.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*36>}36{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The words {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f1\'c8\'ec\'c0\'e7\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  and {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c8\'e7\'c3\'ec\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (Pardoner and Forgiver) indicate that Hashem constantly pardons 
